<DESCRIPT>  BRIEF; PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Mark Langston allowed two hits in seven innings as the California Angels beat
Minnesota 9-1 Thursday night in Minneapolis for their third consecutive
victory over the Twins.;    Langston (15-6) won for the first time in four
starts since July 26, allowing a single to Dan Gladden in the first and an
infield hit to Al Newman in the third. Chris Beasley and Mike Fetters finished
the six-hitter.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LANGSTON, ANGELS TOP TWINS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  A.L. Roundup  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Scott Erickson (15-5) allowed seven hits and five runs in three innings. He
gave up five runs in two-thirds of an inning in his previous start against
Seattle and has allowed 24 earned runs in 30 innings since coming off the
disabled list July 15.; TIGERS 6, WHITE SOX 4: Lou Whitaker and Alan Trammell
drove in three runs each as host Detroit beat Chicago and remained two games
behind first-place Toronto in the American League East.;    The Tigers and
Blue Jays open a three-game series today in Detroit.;    Whitaker hit two home
runs.; BLUE JAYS 4, BREWERS 1: Toronto stopped its longest losing streak in
four years at seven games as the visiting Blue Jays beat Milwaukee behind
Kelly Gruber's two-run homer.;    Gruber, in a 3-for-26 slump, hit his 13th
home run in the fourth inning off Dan Plesac (1-5), putting the Blue Jays
ahead 3-0. Plesac, a three-time All-Star as a reliever, was making just the
second start of his major league career, and the six inning-plus outing was
his longest ever.; RED SOX 6, INDIANS 2: Ellis Burks hit a two-run triple and
rookie Mike Gardiner (5-6) pitched six strong innings as visiting Boston
defeated Cleveland for its seventh victory in eight games.; YANKEES 5, ROYALS
1: Scott Sanderson (12-8) pitched four-hit ball for seven innings as host New
York snapped Kansas City's four-game winning streak.; ORIOLES 9, RANGERS 2:
Jose Mesa celebrated his return from the minors with a three-hitter and rookie
Chito Martinez drove in four runs as host Baltimore completed a four-game
sweep of Texas.  </TEXT>
